<p>In Jetty 8, it was fairly easy to overwrite the standard server port and add an SSL connector in a custom <code>jetty.xml</code> file as follows:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;Configure id="Server" class="org.eclipse.jetty.server.Server"&gt;   &lt;Call name="addConnector"&gt;     &lt;Arg&gt;       &lt;New class="org.eclipse.jetty.server.nio.SelectChannelConnector"&gt;         &lt;Set name="port"&gt;8984&lt;/Set&gt;         &lt;Set name="confidentialPort"&gt;8986&lt;/Set&gt;       &lt;/New&gt;     &lt;/Arg&gt;   &lt;/Call&gt;    &lt;Call name="addConnector"&gt;     &lt;Arg&gt;       &lt;New class="org.eclipse.jetty.server.ssl.SslSelectChannelConnector"&gt;         &lt;Set name="Port"&gt;8986&lt;/Set&gt;         &lt;!-- keystore, password, keyPassword, ... --&gt;       &lt;/New&gt;     &lt;/Arg&gt;   &lt;/Call&gt; &lt;/Configure&gt; </code></pre>  <p>As this configuration is not accepted by Jetty 9 anymore, I have checked out the <a href="http://www.eclipse.org/jetty/documentation/current/configuring-connectors.html" rel="nofollow">Jetty documentation</a> and related StackOverflow issues (like <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/11652058/how-to-override-jetty-xml-with-jetty-port">How to override jetty.xml with jetty.port</a>) without success.</p>  <p>How can the configuration be rewritten to do the same in Jetty 9?</p>